<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
================================================================================
  unattend.xml — MSSQL-on-OCPv lab VM, Windows Server 2022
================================================================================

  Purpose
  =======
  Sysprep answer file used by the OpenShift Virtualization VM catalog when
  cloning a Windows Server 2022 golden image. Drives the VM from "raw clone"
  to "boots to desktop with the data disk formatted and RDP reachable" with
  no manual post-boot steps.

  Sysprep runs three passes against this file: generalize, specialize, and
  oobeSystem. Each <settings pass="..."> block applies to one pass. The
  oobeSystem pass also runs the <FirstLogonCommands> in numerical Order
  (1, 2, 3, ...) the first time the Administrator account logs in.

  Scope and out-of-scope
  ======================
  IN scope (handled automatically by this unattend):
    - Eval-to-Datacenter edition conversion (best-effort).
    - Data-disk initialization and formatting as D:\DATA.
    - RDP firewall + fDenyTSConnections.

  OUT of scope (manual post-boot, documented in docs/windows-vm-prep.md):
    - OpenSSH Server install. The robust install path depends on what your
      cluster lets the VM reach (Microsoft Update for `Add-WindowsCapability`
      vs. github.com for the prebuilt zip vs. neither, in which case an
      RDP drag-and-drop fallback is used). § 4e of the prep doc covers all
      three paths; doing it post-boot keeps this file portable across
      egress-restricted environments.

  Before you use this file
  ========================
  1. Replace BOTH occurrences of YOUR-LAB-PASSWORD below with a real
     throwaway lab password. The AutoLogon password and the
     AdministratorPassword MUST match — if they don't, you'll boot to the
     Windows logon screen instead of straight to the desktop.
  2. Confirm the VM has TWO disks attached at boot: the 60+ GiB OS disk
     (cloned from the golden image) and a separate blank 40 GiB data disk.
     Order 1 (FirstLogonCommand) initializes the second disk as D:\DATA.
  3. The VM keyboard layout, time zone, and locale are hardcoded for
     en-US / Eastern Standard Time below. Adjust for your environment.

  History of pain encoded in this file
  ====================================
  - CD-letter race (2026-06-08): KubeVirt attaches `virtio-win` and
    `unattendCD` as CD-ROMs at boot. Windows grabs D: and E: for them
    before FirstLogonCommands run. The original Order 1 used
    `New-Partition -DriveLetter D` and silently failed because D: was
    already taken. Fixed by moving CDs off D:/E: at the start of Order 1
    before touching the data disk.
  - DISM-broken golden images (2026-06-08): Some captures of the
    engineering golden image have a corrupt servicing stack — `Add-
    WindowsCapability OpenSSH.Server` reports `Installed` but the binaries
    are never deployed, and `dism /Set-Edition` silently no-ops. We keep
    the DISM Set-Edition fallback in Order 2 because it's idempotent
    (no-op when broken); not safe to assume it actually converted the
    edition.
  - GitHub-download OpenSSH install removed from this unattend (2026-06-08):
    An earlier revision (Orders 4-6) downloaded OpenSSH-Win64.zip from
    github.com on first boot. Two problems killed that approach:
    (a) `api.github.com` is commonly allow-listed while the download CDN
        (`objects.githubusercontent.com`) is blocked; the chain hung
        without timing out cleanly.
    (b) The FirstLogonCommands chain halted between Order 3 and Order 4
        on the test image, leaving 4-6 unfired with no diagnostic surface.
    Moved SSH install to a manual § 4e post-boot step with three install
    paths (capability install / GitHub zip / RDP drag-and-drop). Keeps
    this file portable.
================================================================================
-->
<unattend xmlns="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:unattend">

  <!--
  ============================================================================
    Pass 1: generalize (runs during `sysprep /generalize`)
  ============================================================================
  -->
  <settings pass="generalize">
    <!--
      Protect the limited eval-rearm count. If a future Sysprep re-runs
      against this VM, don't burn one of the 5 total rearms. Cheap insurance.
    -->
    <component name="Microsoft-Windows-Security-SPP"
               processorArchitecture="amd64"
               publicKeyToken="31bf3856ad364e35"
               language="neutral" versionScope="nonSxS">
      <SkipRearm>1</SkipRearm>
    </component>
  </settings>

  <!--
  ============================================================================
    Pass 2: specialize (runs once during first boot, before user login)
  ============================================================================
  -->
  <settings pass="specialize">
    <!--
      NO <ProductKey> here — deliberately. Evaluation images (2022 or 2025,
      Standard or Datacenter) self-assign the TIMEBASED_EVAL channel and are
      activated online at first boot by FirstLogonCommands Order 4
      (`slmgr /ato`), which unlocks the full ~180-day eval. No key is needed.

      A hardcoded edition GVLK here is not just unnecessary, it is HARMFUL
      across versions: the WS2022 Datacenter GVLK applied to a Server 2025
      Standard image makes Windows reject the whole specialize pass with
        "Windows could not parse or process the unattend answer file for pass
         [specialize] ... component [Microsoft-Windows-Shell-Setup]"
      and setup falls into the "computer restarted unexpectedly" loop
      (observed 2026-06-17 bringing the 2025 golden image up on a new cluster).
      Keep this answer file edition/version-agnostic.
    -->

    <!--
      Extend the OS partition (C:) to consume all unallocated space on
      the OS disk. The golden image is captured smaller than the cloned
      DV; this grows C: to fill the actual provisioned size.
    -->
    <component name="Microsoft-Windows-Deployment"
               processorArchitecture="amd64"
               publicKeyToken="31bf3856ad364e35"
               language="neutral" versionScope="nonSxS">
      <ExtendOSPartition><Extend>true</Extend></ExtendOSPartition>
    </component>
  </settings>

  <!--
  ============================================================================
    Pass 3: oobeSystem (skip the OOBE wizard + first-login automation)
  ============================================================================
  -->
  <settings pass="oobeSystem">
    <component xmlns:wcm="http://schemas.microsoft.com/WMIConfig/2002/State"
               xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
               name="Microsoft-Windows-Shell-Setup"
               processorArchitecture="amd64"
               publicKeyToken="31bf3856ad364e35"
               language="neutral" versionScope="nonSxS">

      <!-- Skip every wizard page. Boot straight to desktop. -->
      <OOBE>
        <HideEULAPage>true</HideEULAPage>
        <HideOEMRegistrationScreen>true</HideOEMRegistrationScreen>
        <HideOnlineAccountScreens>true</HideOnlineAccountScreens>
        <HideWirelessSetupInOOBE>true</HideWirelessSetupInOOBE>
        <NetworkLocation>Work</NetworkLocation>
        <SkipUserOOBE>true</SkipUserOOBE>
        <SkipMachineOOBE>true</SkipMachineOOBE>
        <ProtectYourPC>3</ProtectYourPC>
      </OOBE>

      <!--
        AutoLogon: log Administrator in automatically on first boot so
        FirstLogonCommands actually fires. The Password here MUST match
        the AdministratorPassword below — if they differ, AutoLogon fails
        and you'll see the lock screen instead.
      -->
      <AutoLogon>
        <Password><Value>YOUR-LAB-PASSWORD</Value><PlainText>true</PlainText></Password>
        <Enabled>true</Enabled>
        <Username>Administrator</Username>
      </AutoLogon>

      <!-- Set the Administrator account password. Must match AutoLogon above. -->
      <UserAccounts>
        <AdministratorPassword>
          <Value>YOUR-LAB-PASSWORD</Value><PlainText>true</PlainText>
        </AdministratorPassword>
      </UserAccounts>

      <RegisteredOrganization/>
      <RegisteredOwner/>
      <TimeZone>Eastern Standard Time</TimeZone>

      <!--
        ==================================================================
        FirstLogonCommands — run on first Administrator login, in Order.
        Synchronous: command N+1 doesn't start until command N exits.
        A nonzero exit DOES NOT halt the chain — subsequent commands still
        run. Logs land in C:\Windows\Panther\UnattendGC\setupact.log.
        ==================================================================
      -->
      <FirstLogonCommands>

        <!--
        ============================================================
        Order 1 — Disk init: move CDs off D:/E:, then format data disk as D:
        ============================================================
        Why the CD-shuffle first: KubeVirt attaches `virtio-win` and
        `unattendCD` as CD-ROMs, and Windows hands them D: and E: at
        boot before this command runs. If we go straight to
        `New-Partition -DriveLetter D` it errors "drive letter D in use"
        and the entire pipeline aborts — leaving the data disk
        initialized (with just the GPT MSR partition) but with no
        usable D: volume.

        DriveType=5 means CD-ROM in Win32_Volume; the filter is
        deliberately narrow so we don't accidentally move a fixed disk
        if a user has unusual letter assignments.
        ============================================================
        -->
        <SynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
          <Order>1</Order>
          <CommandLine>powershell.exe -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Command "Get-CimInstance Win32_Volume | Where-Object { $_.DriveLetter -eq 'D:' -and $_.DriveType -eq 5 } | ForEach-Object { Set-CimInstance -InputObject $_ -Property @{DriveLetter='X:'} }; Get-CimInstance Win32_Volume | Where-Object { $_.DriveLetter -eq 'E:' -and $_.DriveType -eq 5 } | ForEach-Object { Set-CimInstance -InputObject $_ -Property @{DriveLetter='Y:'} }; Get-Disk | Where-Object { $_.PartitionStyle -eq 'RAW' -or $_.PartitionStyle -eq 'Uninitialized' } | Initialize-Disk -PartitionStyle GPT -PassThru | New-Partition -UseMaximumSize -DriveLetter D | Format-Volume -FileSystem NTFS -NewFileSystemLabel DATA -Confirm:$false -Force"</CommandLine>
          <Description>Move CD-ROMs off D:/E:, then initialize and format data disk as D: NTFS DATA</Description>
          <RequiresUserInput>false</RequiresUserInput>
        </SynchronousCommand>

        <!--
        ============================================================
        Order 2 — Edition conversion fallback (best-effort)
        ============================================================
        The specialize-pass <ProductKey> SHOULD have already flipped
        the install from ServerDatacenterEval to ServerDatacenter.
        This is a belt-and-suspenders fallback: if findstr still finds
        "ServerDatacenterEval" in the current edition, run dism's
        Set-Edition. The `&amp;&amp;` short-circuits so dism is skipped
        if the conversion already happened.

        Caveat: on DISM-broken images (observed 2026-06-08),
        `dism /Get-CurrentEdition` itself errors with "file not
        found." findstr will not match the eval string and dism
        won't run — leaving the install on the 10-day eval grace
        loop. Recoverable via `slmgr /rearm`; documented in the
        prep doc.
        ============================================================
        -->
        <SynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
          <Order>2</Order>
          <CommandLine>cmd /c "dism /online /Get-CurrentEdition | findstr /i ServerDatacenterEval &amp;&amp; dism /online /Set-Edition:ServerDatacenter /ProductKey:WX4NM-KYWYW-QJJR4-XV3QB-6VM33 /AcceptEula /NoRestart"</CommandLine>
          <Description>Best-effort Eval to Datacenter conversion. No-op on DISM-broken images.</Description>
          <RequiresUserInput>false</RequiresUserInput>
        </SynchronousCommand>

        <!--
        ============================================================
        Order 3 — Enable RDP
        ============================================================
        Two things needed for RDP to work: firewall rule open
        ("Remote Desktop" rule group) and the registry flag
        fDenyTSConnections set to 0 (allows incoming RDP connections).
        File and Printer Sharing is enabled too so ping/SMB diagnostics
        work from the host network.
        ============================================================
        -->
        <SynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
          <Order>3</Order>
          <CommandLine>powershell.exe -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Command "Enable-NetFirewallRule -DisplayGroup 'File and Printer Sharing'; Enable-NetFirewallRule -DisplayGroup 'Remote Desktop'; Set-ItemProperty -Path 'HKLM:\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\Terminal Server' -Name 'fDenyTSConnections' -Value 0"</CommandLine>
          <Description>Enable RDP firewall rule and turn off fDenyTSConnections</Description>
          <RequiresUserInput>false</RequiresUserInput>
        </SynchronousCommand>

        <!--
        ============================================================
        Order 4 — Fix the NIC MTU to match the cluster overlay
        ============================================================
        MUST run before activation (Order 5). KubeVirt/OVN advertises a
        reduced MTU (commonly 1400) via DHCP, but Windows IGNORES the
        DHCP MTU option and stays at 1500. The guest then emits 1500-byte
        packets into a 1400 overlay; small packets (TCP handshake, SSH)
        pass, but large ones (TLS handshakes, the activation exchange,
        big downloads) are dropped and PMTU discovery is black-holed —
        so HTTPS just times out (slmgr /ato -> 0x80072EE2). Setting the
        guest MTU to the overlay size fixes it (verified 2026-06-17:
        1500 -> 1400 made activation succeed instantly).

        1400 matches the standard OVN-Kubernetes pod MTU. If your cluster
        differs, set this to the launcher pod's eth0 MTU
        (`oc exec <virt-launcher-pod> -c compute -- cat /sys/class/net/eth0/mtu`).
        ============================================================
        -->
        <SynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
          <Order>4</Order>
          <CommandLine>netsh interface ipv4 set subinterface "Ethernet" mtu=1400 store=persistent</CommandLine>
          <Description>Lower NIC MTU to 1400 to match the OVN overlay (Windows ignores DHCP MTU)</Description>
          <RequiresUserInput>false</RequiresUserInput>
        </SynchronousCommand>

        <!--
        ============================================================
        Order 5 — Activate the evaluation over the internet
        ============================================================
        THIS is what gives each clone its full ~180-day evaluation.
        A freshly generalized eval clone boots into "Initial grace
        period" with only ~10 days remaining — that 10 days is the
        "activate within 10 days or auto-shutdown" deadline, NOT the
        eval length. `slmgr /ato` performs the online activation, which
        flips the clock to the full ~180-day timed-eval window
        (verified 2026-06-17: 10 days -> expiry 12/14/2026). sysprep
        /generalize resets activation, so this MUST run per clone on
        first boot — it cannot be baked into the shared golden image.

        Depends on Order 4 (MTU): without it, the activation HTTPS call
        times out (0x80072EE2). Also requires the cluster to allow
        outbound 443 to *.sls.microsoft.com (un-intercepted). Where that
        is unavailable it is a harmless no-op and the clone keeps the
        10-day grace; re-run `slmgr /ato` once reachable.
        ============================================================
        -->
        <SynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
          <Order>5</Order>
          <CommandLine>cscript //nologo C:\Windows\System32\slmgr.vbs /ato</CommandLine>
          <Description>Activate the evaluation online to unlock the full ~180-day eval window</Description>
          <RequiresUserInput>false</RequiresUserInput>
        </SynchronousCommand>

        <!--
        ============================================================
        OpenSSH Server install is intentionally NOT done here.
        ============================================================
        An earlier revision had Orders 4-6 download OpenSSH-Win64.zip
        from github.com and register the service. Two problems forced
        the move to a manual post-boot install:
          1. Many clusters allow `api.github.com` but block the
             release-download CDN (`objects.githubusercontent.com`),
             causing the download to hang past Sysprep's per-command
             window.
          2. On the test image, the FirstLogonCommands chain halted
             between Order 3 and Order 4 with no diagnostic surface,
             leaving Orders 4-6 unfired even when the download URL
             was reachable.

        OpenSSH install is now a manual step. See
        docs/windows-vm-prep.md section 4e for three install paths
        (capability install / GitHub zip / RDP drag-and-drop) and
        pick whichever matches your cluster's egress posture.
        ============================================================
        -->


      </FirstLogonCommands>
    </component>
  </settings>
</unattend>
